WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:20.000
A list is a collection of items with a single item written on each line and they're everywhere

6
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Shopping lists to do lists even bucket lists. A list of all the things a person would like to do before they die

7
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
In fact, there's an episode of 6-minute English all about them.

8
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Imagine you're at the supermarket and find someone's shopping list. This happens a lot to Joe Nolan, a linguistics researcher, whose new book explores our love of lists.

9
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Here's Joe reading her shopping list on BBC Radio 4 program Word of mouth.

10
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
I only list the first four items, but the list read

11
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And Narnas, I.I.P.K.

12
00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Shrooms

13
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Narnas, I.I.P.K. Shrooms

14
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Can you work out what Joe was buying at the supermarket fill?

15
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Okay, well, I'm going to guess that Narnas are bananas and shrooms. They've got to be mushrooms, right?

16
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Okay, but what about I.I. and P.K.K.

17
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
What could they mean?

18
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Well, here's Joe's explanation to Michael Rosen, presenter of BBC Radio 4's Word of mouth.

19
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And let's just come back to Puk. I mean, were you instructing yourself to be sick in the supermarket?

20
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I just a bit lost it.

21
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
No, it's slightly grotesque. My husband doesn't like Pukumber.

22
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Any abbreviation for Pukumber would be Puk. So he is always referred to it as Puk.

23
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Aha! Cucumbers make Joe and his husband Puk. A slang word for vomit.

24
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And Puk rhymes with Cuk. So it's a way of reminding her to buy cucumbers.

25
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Wow, sometimes lists are like secret codes.

26
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
In this episode, we'll find out why people love lists.

27
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.000
And learn some useful new words and phrases.

28
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And remember, you'll find another list of all the vocabulary used on our website.

29
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

30
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
But first, a question for you, Beth.

31
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
According to the list on the Internet Movie Database website,

32
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
which movie has made the most money ever.

33
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Is it a, Titanic?

34
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
B, Avengers Endgame?

35
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Or C, Avatar?

36
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
I think it might be Avatar, although that might have been the most expensive to make.

37
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:42.000
I'm not sure.

38
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Okay, well, we'll find out at the end of the program.

39
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Popular songs are full of lists.

40
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And one of the most famous is my favourite things.

41
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Song by Judy Andrews in the film, The Sound of Music.

42
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:02.000
The song lists all her favourite things from rain drops on roses to whiskers on kittens.

43
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Here, Joe Nolan and Michael Rose and discussed the song on BBC Radio 4 program, Word of Mouth.

44
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
I feel like you get a lot of big burn for your back in that song.

45
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Maybe it's the positivity, it's a bit saccharine, maybe that's also part of the issue.

46
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
The listing courage is you to think really efficiently and economically.

47
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:30.000
So I think you don't waste a lot of time and effort making a nice sentence or using long words.

48
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
You just get to the number of things quite quickly.

49
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
The song's list of favourite things is long.

50
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And Joe says you get a big bang for your buck.

51
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
An idiom meaning that you gain a lot in return for the money or effort you spend on something,

52
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.000
but not everyone likes the song.

53
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Some call it saccharine, an adjective meaning excessively sweet, sentimental or insincere.

54
00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Lists often abbreviate the items they contain.

55
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
So you get to the number of things quickly.

56
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
The number of something means the most important or essential point about it.

57
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Lists can be useful as well.

58
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Here's Joe Nolan giving an example of a useful list to BBC Radio 4's Word of Mouth.

59
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
I find a mind who makes pros and cons lists.

60
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Find that it really helps her resolve a situation.

61
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.000
She halves her page, pros, cons and she's set by the end of it.

62
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
She knows what she's doing.

63
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Lists help us make decisions by writing down all the pros and cons of a situation.

64
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
The pros and cons is another way of saying the advantages and disadvantages of something,

65
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
especially when you're trying to choose between them.

66
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:49.000
The more you think about it, the more you see lists everywhere in menus and bank statements,

67
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.000
for example, and therapists even recommend listing all the good things in your life to feel happier.

68
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Not bad for a few words on a scrap of paper.

69
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Okay, it's time to reveal the answer to my question.

70
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Beth, I asked you which movie had made the most money ever.

71
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:17.000
And you said, Avertar, and now according to the Internet Movie database, that's exactly right.

72
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Yay!

73
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with Bucket List.

74
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.000
All the things you would like to do before you die.

75
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Luke is slang for vomit or sick.

76
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.000
If something gives bang for your buck, you gain a lot of extra value in return for the money or effort you put into it.

77
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
If you call something saccharine, you criticize it for being too sweet or sentimental.

78
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
The number of a problem or situation is the most important or essential thing about it.

79
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And finally, something's pros and cons are its advantages and disadvantages.

80
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember, you'll find a quiz and worksheet for this episode over on our website,

81
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
BBCLanningEnglish.com.

82
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Goodbye for now.

83
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Bye!
